value.value: A heterodimeric E1 complex that activates the ubiquitin-like protein NEDD8. In humans the subunits are NAE1 (also known as APPBP1) and UBA3.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-methionyl-[F-actin] + NADPH + O2 + H+ = L-methionyl-(R)-S-oxide-[F-actin] + NADP+ + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: an (omega-1)-ethyl fatty acid + O2 + reduced [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase] = an (omega-1)-hydroxy fatty acid + H+ + H2O + oxidized [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase].

label.value: medium-chain fatty acid omega-1 hydroxylase activity

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: an (omega-1)-ethyl medium-chain fatty acid + O2 + reduced [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase] = an (omega-1)-hydroxy-medium-chain fatty acid + H+ + H2O + oxidized [NADPH-hemoprotein reductase. A medium-chain fatty acid has an aliphatic tail containing 6 to 12 carbons.

definition.value: While there is not universal consensus on the lengths of short-, medium-, long- and very-long-chain fatty acids, the GO uses the definitions in ChEBI (see CHEBI:26666, CHEBI:59554, CHEBI:15904 and CHEBI:27283).

value.value: A heterodimeric complex capable of glycosyltransferase activity required for the elongation of heparan sulfate chains. In humans, the complex consists of EXT1 and EXT2. In Drosophila, the complex consists of ttv and sotv.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysyl79-[histone H3] + S-adenosyl-L-methionine = H+ + N6-methyl-L-lysyl79-[histone H3] + S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.
Catalysis of the reaction: L-lysyl79-[histone H3] + 2 S-adenosyl-L-methionine = 2H+ + N6,N6-methyl-L-lysyl79-[histone H3] + 2 S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine.

A protein complex that catalyzes the base-exchange of a guanine residue with queuine at the wobble position of the anticodon of tRNAs. The eukaryotic tRNA-guanine transglycosylase exists as a heterodimer of a catalytic subunit (QTRT1 in humans) and an accessory subunit (QTRT2 in humans), whereas the bacterial enzyme is homodimeric.

A protein complex capable of catalyzing the reaction of GTP and mannose-1-phosphate to form GDP-mannose. The complex is a homodimer in most bacteria and a heterodimer in most eukaryotes. In humans, it is composed of a catalytic beta subunit (GMPPB) and a regulatory alpha subunit (GMPPA).
Catalysis of the reaction: (R)-glycerate + NADP+ = 3-hydroxypyruvate + NADPH + H+.

A protein complex capable of condensing two 2Fe-2S clusters into one 4Fe-4S center in mitochondria. In S. cerevisiae, it consists of Isa1 and Isa2. In humans it consists of ISCA1 and ISCA2. Additional proteins may be present.
Catalysis of the reaction: methyl (2E,6E)-farnesoate + O2 + reduced [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase] = H+ + H2O + juvenile hormone III + oxidized [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase].
Catalysis of the reaction: (2E,6E)-farnesoate + O2 + reduced [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase] = H+ + H2O + juvenile hormone III carboxylate + oxidized [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase].

A protein complex capable of catalysing the transfer of the 3-amino-3-carboxypropyl group from S-adenosyl-L-methionine (SAM) to the histidine residue of translation elongation factor 2 (EF2), which is the first step in the biosynthesis of diphthamide. The complex is a Dph2 homodimer in archaea and a Dph1-Dph2 heterodimer in eukaryotes.
Catalysis of the reaction: a 3'-hydro-2'-hydroxy-beta-oxodihydrochalcone + UDP-alpha-D-glucose = a 3'-(beta-D-glucopyranosyl)-2'-hydroxy-beta-oxodihydrochalcone + H+ + UDP.
Catalysis of the reaction: a fatty acid + ATP + CoA = a fatty acyl-CoA + AMP + diphosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction: a diacylglycerol + H2O = a fatty acid + a monoacylglycerol + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: inositol pentakisphosphate + ATP = inositol hexakisphosphate + ADP + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction: acetyl-CoA + N-terminal L-methionyl-[protein] = CoA + H+ + N-terminal N(alpha)-acetyl-L-methionyl-[protein].
Catalysis of the reaction: acetyl-CoA + N-terminal L-methionyl-[tubulin] = CoA + H+ + N-terminal N(alpha)-acetyl-L-methionyl-[tubulin]. The N-terminus of both alpha- and beta-tubulin are acetylated.

Catalysis of the reaction: a 1,2-saturated fatty acid + 2 Fe(II)-[cytochrome b5] + 2 H+ + O2 = a (R)-2-hydroxy fatty acid + 2 Fe(III)-[cytochrome b5] + H2O. Note that the substrate is a free fatty acid, not a fatty acyl chain within a sphingolipid.
Catalysis of the reaction: an N-(1,2 saturated acyl)-(4R)-hydroxysphinganine + 2 Fe(II)-[cytochrome b5] + 2 H+ + O2 = an N-(2R-hydroxyacyl)-4R-hydroxysphinganine + 2 Fe(III)-[cytochrome b5] + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: a short-chain 2,3-saturated fatty acyl-CoA + O2 = a short-chain (2E)-enoyl-CoA + H2O2.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: a medium-chain 2,3-saturated fatty acyl-CoA + O2 = a medium-chain (2E)-enoyl-CoA + H2O2.

definition.value: While there is not universal consensus on the lengths of short-, medium-, long- and very-long-chain fatty acids, the GO uses the definitions in ChEBI (see CHEBI:26666, CHEBI:59554, CHEBI:15904 and CHEBI:27283).

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: a long-chain 2,3-saturated fatty acyl-CoA + O2 = a long-chain (2E)-enoyl-CoA + H2O2.

definition.value: While there is not universal consensus on the lengths of short-, medium-, long- and very-long-chain fatty acids, the GO uses the definitions in ChEBI (see CHEBI:26666, CHEBI:59554, CHEBI:15904 and CHEBI:27283).

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: choline = acetaldehyde + trimethylamine.

definition.value: Note that this term has a MetaCyc pathway reference as the pathway only has a single step.

value.value: Catalysis of the reaction: an L-polyhomomethionine + 2 O2 + 2 reduced [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase] = an (E)-omega-(methylsulfanyl)-alkanal oxime + CO2 + 2 H(+) + 3 H2O + 2 oxidized [NADPH--hemoprotein reductase].
Catalysis of the reaction: 3'-phosphoadenylyl sulfate + an aliphatic (Z)-desulfo-glucosinolate = a (Z)-omega-(methylsulfanyl)-N-sulfo-alkylhydroximate S-glucoside + adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate + H+.

Catalysis of the reactions: a 2-(omega-methylsulfanyl)alkylmalate = a 2-(omega-methylsulfanyl)alkylmaleate + H2O and a 3-(omega-methylsulfanyl)alkylmalate = a 2-(omega-methylsulfanyl)alkylmaleate + H2O.
Catalysis of the reaction: (-)-secoisolariciresinol + 2 NAD+ = (-)-matairesinol + 2 H(+) + 2 NADH.
A protein complex that regulates the TORC1 signaling pathway in response to nutrients. The KICSTOR complex is composed of KPTN, ITFG2, C12orf66 and SZT2.
The directed movement of L-aspartate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
Enables the transfer of D-aspartate from one side of a membrane to the other.
One of the two nuclear divisions that occur as part of the meiotic cell cycle.

A mitotic cell cycle process comprising the steps by which the nucleus of a eukaryotic cell divides; the process involves condensation of chromosomal DNA into a highly compacted form. Canonically, mitosis produces two daughter nuclei whose chromosome complement is identical to that of the mother cell.
Any process that modulates the ability of the cytoplasmic translational apparatus to interpret the genetic code.
A protein complex that possesses DNA methyltransferase activity.
The process in which ADP is transported across a mitochondrial membrane, into or out of the mitochondrion.
A giant secretory organelle that comprises a bulb-shape capsule containing a coiled hollow tubule structure attached to it. A cnida defines the phylum Cnidaria.
The removal of an amine group from an adenosine to produce inosine within a tRNA molecule.

label.value: plus-end-directed endosome transport along mitotic spindle midzone microtubule

value.value: The directed movement of an endosome towards the plus end of a microtubule, mediated by motor proteins. This process begins with the attachment of an endosome to a microtubule, and ends when the endosome reaches its final destination.

label.value: contractile vacuole tethering involved in discharge

value.value: The initial, indirect interaction between a contractile vacuole membrane and a site of discharge in the plasma membrane. This interaction is mediated by tethering factors (or complexes), which interact with both membranes. Interaction can occur via direct binding to membrane phospholipids or membrane proteins, or via binding to vesicle coat proteins. This process is distinct from and prior to docking and fusion.

label.value: contractile vacuole dissociation from plasma membrane

value.value: The dissociation of the contractile vacuole after discharge, from the plasma membrane. This interaction is mediated by detethering factors that initiate the process of tubulation and fragmentation of the empty contractile vacuole bladder, which is then reincorporated into the CV network.
The directed movement of the contractile vacuole to a specific location.

label.value: pore formation during contractile vacuole discharge

value.value: The formation of a transient pore in the plasma membrane and the attached contractile vacuolar membrane, to release water from the cell. This process does not involve fusion of the two membranes.
The cellular processes that contribute to exocytosis.
Binding to a protein upon post-translation modification of the target protein.

definition.value: This term should only be used when the binding is shown to require a post-translational modification: the interaction needs to be tested with and without the PTM. The binding does not need to be at the site of the modification. It may be that the PTM causes a conformational change that allows binding of the protein to another region; this type of modification-dependent protein binding is valid for annotation to this term.

value.value: Binding to a protein upon phosphorylation of the target protein.

definition.value: This term should only be used when the binding is shown to require phosphorylation of the target protein: the interaction needs to be tested with and without the PTM. The binding does not need to be at the site of phosphorylation. It may be that the phosphorylation causes a conformational change that allows binding of the protein to another region; this type of phosphorylation-dependent protein binding is valid for annotation to this term.
